03819nam a22005535i 9789048553495DE-B159720240306015011.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485534957 a10.1515/97890485534952doi  a(DE-B1597)664218  a(OCoLC)1382315711  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aART0170002bisacsh04a006.71 aBlom, Joleen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aVideo Game Characters and Transmedia Storytelling :bThe Dynamic Game Character /cJoleen Blom. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGames and Play ;v900tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tA brief note on Japanese names and words -- t1. Introducing the dynamic game character -- t2. Characters in contemporary media -- t3. How the dynamic game character develops -- t4. Strategies to control a character's transtextual identities -- t5. Parasocial relationships with nonplayable characters -- t6. The construction of transmedia game characters -- t7. The future of dynamic game characters -- tGlossary: A brief typology of characters -- tGeneral bibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aCharacters are a vital aspect of today's transmedia practices. Combining theories on fictional persons from Japanese and Euro-American practices, this book discusses video game characters embedded in our popular media culture in which they are constantly produced and re-imagined. This book introduces the dynamic game character, a type of game character with a development structure that consists of multiple outcomes in a game. Through their actions and choices, players can influence these game characters' identities and affect their possible destinies. Games subvert the idea that fictional persons must maintain a coherent identity. This book shows that dynamic game characters challenge strategies of top-down control through close readings of the Mass Effect series, Persona 5, Hades, Animal Crossing: New Horizons and more. It is directed to all scholars interested in the topics of transmedia storytelling, video games, characters, and Japanese narratology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aGame Studies. 4aMedia Studies. 7aART / Mixed Media.2bisacsh  aDynamic Game Characters, transmedia practices, game studies, reader-response theory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102374840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048553495?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048553495zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048553495/original  a978-3-11-102374-8 Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA